## P1 ‚Äî `eval_hash` can return a term beyond its configured `max_*` limits: ACCEPTED, fixed

Reproduced exactly: `FALSE` with `max_node_depth=1` returned a depth-2 term
(spent 3), and `max_materialized_nodes=1` returned a size-3 term ‚Äî both breach
the documented `ResourceFault` contract because the size/depth fence only fired
at `steps % 256 == 0`, and `FALSE` normalizes in 3 steps. Not a canonical hash
split (resource faults are local/non-canonical, ¬ß3.6), but a `max_*` control
that a completed return can exceed is exactly the "public safety controls
unreliable" you flagged.

Fix (your recommendation 3, minimal form): the size/depth test is factored
into `resource_check(t, limits)` and called BOTH on the 256-step in-flight
sample AND immediately before the normal-form return. The DISSONANCE returns
(ATP Exhausted / Unresolved) are size-1 leaves and cannot breach, so they need
no check. Regression cases added to the oracle self-test, all four you
required:
- `FALSE`, `max_node_depth=1` ‚Üí `ResourceFault("term depth")`;
- `FALSE`, `max_materialized_nodes=1` ‚Üí `ResourceFault("term growth")`;
- exact-bound control (`depth=2`, `size=3`) returns normally (size 3, spent 3);
- depth-1500 and Omega tests unchanged; all 49 Book I vectors byte- and
  ATP-identical; `run_reference` and every proof bridge still green.

**Rust parity:** the Rust implementation (`impl-rs`) is a conformance
replayer and exposes **no** configurable resource limits ‚Äî it has no
`max_node_depth`/`max_materialized_nodes` and no `ResourceFault`. These
controls are therefore explicitly **Python-oracle-local** (the vectors, which
Rust replays, carry no resource-limit inputs and never exercise ResourceFault
‚Äî faults are non-canonical by ¬ß3.6). Documented here rather than pinned into
Rust, per your "either pin parity or document Python-local."

